redisCommands.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.
redisCommands.name: SDIFFSTORE
redisCommands.summary: Subtract multiple sets and store the resulting set in a key

redisCommands.name: SELECT
redisCommands.summary: Change the selected database for the current connection

redisCommands.name: SET
redisCommands.summary: Set the string value of a key

redisCommands.name: SETBIT
redisCommands.summary: Sets or clears the bit at offset in the string value stored at key

redisCommands.name: SETEX
redisCommands.summary: Set the value and expiration of a key

redisCommands.name: SETNX
redisCommands.summary: Set the value of a key, only if the key does not exist

redisCommands.complexity: O(1), not counting the time taken to copy the new string in place. Usually, this string is very small so the amortized complexity is O(1). Otherwise, complexity is O(M) with M being the length of the value argument.
redisCommands.name: SETRANGE
redisCommands.summary: Overwrite part of a string at key starting at the specified offset

redisCommands.name: SHUTDOWN
redisCommands.summary: Synchronously save the dataset to disk and then shut down the server

redisCommands.complexity: O(N*M) worst case where N is the cardinality of the smallest set and M is the number of sets.
redisCommands.name: SINTER
redisCommands.summary: Intersect multiple sets

redisCommands.complexity: O(N*M) worst case where N is the cardinality of the smallest set and M is the number of sets.
redisCommands.name: SINTERSTORE
redisCommands.summary: Intersect multiple sets and store the resulting set in a key

redisCommands.name: SISMEMBER
redisCommands.summary: Determine if a given value is a member of a set

redisCommands.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements being checked for membership
redisCommands.name: SMISMEMBER
redisCommands.summary: Returns the membership associated with the given elements for a set

redisCommands.name: SLAVEOF
redisCommands.summary: Make the server a replica of another instance, or promote it as master. Deprecated starting with Redis 5. Use REPLICAOF instead.

redisCommands.name: REPLICAOF
redisCommands.summary: Make the server a replica of another instance, or promote it as master.

redisCommands.name: SLOWLOG
redisCommands.summary: Manages the Redis slow queries log

redisCommands.complexity: O(N) where N is the set cardinality.
redisCommands.name: SMEMBERS
redisCommands.summary: Get all the members in a set

redisCommands.name: SMOVE
redisCommands.summary: Move a member from one set to another

redisCommands.complexity: O(N+M*log(M)) where N is the number of elements in the list or set to sort, and M the number of returned elements. When the elements are not sorted, complexity is currently O(N) as there is a copy step that will be avoided in next releases.
redisCommands.name: SORT
redisCommands.summary: Sort the elements in a list, set or sorted set

redisCommands.name: SPOP
redisCommands.summary: Remove and return one or multiple random members from a set

redisCommands.complexity: Without the count argument O(1), otherwise O(N) where N is the absolute value of the passed count.
redisCommands.name: SRANDMEMBER
redisCommands.summary: Get one or multiple random members from a set

redisCommands.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of members to be removed.
redisCommands.name: SREM
redisCommands.summary: Remove one or more members from a set

redisCommands.complexity: For LCS O(strlen(s1)*strlen(s2))
redisCommands.name: STRALGO
redisCommands.summary: Run algorithms (currently LCS) against strings

redisCommands.name: STRLEN
redisCommands.summary: Get the length of the value stored in a key

redisCommands.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of channels to subscribe to.
redisCommands.name: SUBSCRIBE
redisCommands.summary: Listen for messages published to the given channels

redisCommands.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.
redisCommands.name: SUNION
redisCommands.summary: Add multiple sets

redisCommands.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.
redisCommands.name: SUNIONSTORE
redisCommands.summary: Add multiple sets and store the resulting set in a key

redisCommands.name: SWAPDB
redisCommands.summary: Swaps two Redis databases

redisCommands.name: SYNC
redisCommands.summary: Internal command used for replication

redisCommands.name: PSYNC
redisCommands.summary: Internal command used for replication

redisCommands.name: TIME
redisCommands.summary: Return the current server time

redisCommands.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys that will be touched.
redisCommands.name: TOUCH
redisCommands.summary: Alters the last access time of a key(s). Returns the number of existing keys specified.

redisCommands.name: TTL
redisCommands.summary: Get the time to live for a key

redisCommands.name: TYPE
redisCommands.summary: Determine the type stored at key

redisCommands.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of clients already subscribed to a channel.
redisCommands.name: UNSUBSCRIBE
redisCommands.summary: Stop listening for messages posted to the given channels

redisCommands.complexity: O(1) for each key removed regardless of its size. Then the command does O(N) work in a different thread in order to reclaim memory, where N is the number of allocations the deleted objects where composed of.
redisCommands.name: UNLINK
redisCommands.summary: Delete a key asynchronously in another thread. Otherwise it is just as DEL, but non blocking.

redisCommands.name: UNWATCH
redisCommands.summary: Forget about all watched keys

redisCommands.name: WAIT
redisCommands.summary: Wait for the synchronous replication of all the write commands sent in the context of the current connection

redisCommands.complexity: O(1) for every key.
redisCommands.name: WATCH
redisCommands.summary: Watch the given keys to determine execution of the MULTI/EXEC block

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)) for each item added, where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.
redisCommands.name: ZADD
redisCommands.summary: Add one or more members to a sorted set, or update its score if it already exists

redisCommands.name: ZCARD
redisCommands.summary: Get the number of members in a sorted set

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set.
redisCommands.name: ZCOUNT
redisCommands.summary: Count the members in a sorted set with scores within the given values

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)) where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.
redisCommands.name: ZINCRBY
redisCommands.summary: Increment the score of a member in a sorted set

redisCommands.complexity: O(N*K)+O(M*log(M)) worst case with N being the smallest input sorted set, K being the number of input sorted sets and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.
redisCommands.name: ZINTER
redisCommands.summary: Intersect multiple sorted sets

redisCommands.complexity: O(N*K)+O(M*log(M)) worst case with N being the smallest input sorted set, K being the number of input sorted sets and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.
redisCommands.name: ZINTERSTORE
redisCommands.summary: Intersect multiple sorted sets and store the resulting sorted set in a new key

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set.
redisCommands.name: ZLEXCOUNT
redisCommands.summary: Count the number of members in a sorted set between a given lexicographical range

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)*M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set, and M being the number of elements popped.
redisCommands.name: ZPOPMAX
redisCommands.summary: Remove and return members with the highest scores in a sorted set

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)*M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set, and M being the number of elements popped.
redisCommands.name: ZPOPMIN
redisCommands.summary: Remove and return members with the lowest scores in a sorted set

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements returned.
redisCommands.name: ZRANGE
redisCommands.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by index

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).
redisCommands.name: ZRANGEBYLEX
redisCommands.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by lexicographical range

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).
redisCommands.name: ZREVRANGEBYLEX
redisCommands.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by lexicographical range, ordered from higher to lower strings.

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).
redisCommands.name: ZRANGEBYSCORE
redisCommands.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by score

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N))
redisCommands.name: ZRANK
redisCommands.summary: Determine the index of a member in a sorted set

redisCommands.complexity: O(M*log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements to be removed.
redisCommands.name: ZREM
redisCommands.summary: Remove one or more members from a sorted set

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements removed by the operation.
redisCommands.name: ZREMRANGEBYLEX
redisCommands.summary: Remove all members in a sorted set between the given lexicographical range

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements removed by the operation.
redisCommands.name: ZREMRANGEBYRANK
redisCommands.summary: Remove all members in a sorted set within the given indexes

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements removed by the operation.
redisCommands.name: ZREMRANGEBYSCORE
redisCommands.summary: Remove all members in a sorted set within the given scores

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements returned.
redisCommands.name: ZREVRANGE
redisCommands.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by index, with scores ordered from high to low

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).
redisCommands.name: ZREVRANGEBYSCORE
redisCommands.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by score, with scores ordered from high to low

redisCommands.complexity: O(log(N))
redisCommands.name: ZREVRANK
redisCommands.summary: Determine the index of a member in a sorted set, with scores ordered from high to low

redisCommands.name: ZSCORE
redisCommands.summary: Get the score associated with the given member in a sorted set

redisCommands.complexity: O(N)+O(M*log(M)) with N being the sum of the sizes of the input sorted sets, and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.
redisCommands.name: ZUNION
redisCommands.summary: Add multiple sorted sets

redisCommands.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of members being requested.
redisCommands.name: ZMSCORE
redisCommands.summary: Get the score associated with the given members in a sorted set

redisCommands.complexity: O(N)+O(M log(M)) with N being the sum of the sizes of the input sorted sets, and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.
redisCommands.name: ZUNIONSTORE
redisCommands.summary: Add multiple sorted sets and store the resulting sorted set in a new key

redisCommands.complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection.
redisCommands.name: SCAN
redisCommands.summary: Incrementally iterate the keys space

redisCommands.complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection..
redisCommands.name: SSCAN
redisCommands.summary: Incrementally iterate Set elements

redisCommands.complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection..
redisCommands.name: HSCAN
redisCommands.summary: Incrementally iterate hash fields and associated values

redisCommands.complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection..
redisCommands.name: ZSCAN
redisCommands.summary: Incrementally iterate sorted sets elements and associated scores

redisCommands.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of returned items for the subcommands CONSUMERS and GROUPS. The STREAM subcommand is O(log N) with N being the number of items in the stream.
redisCommands.name: XINFO
redisCommands.summary: Get information on streams and consumer groups

redisCommands.name: XADD
redisCommands.summary: Appends a new entry to a stream

redisCommands.complexity: O(N), with N being the number of evicted entries. Constant times are very small however, since entries are organized in macro nodes containing multiple entries that can be released with a single deallocation.
redisCommands.name: XTRIM
redisCommands.summary: Trims the stream to (approximately if '~' is passed) a certain size

redisCommands.complexity: O(1) for each single item to delete in the stream, regardless of the stream size.
redisCommands.name: XDEL
redisCommands.summary: Removes the specified entries from the stream. Returns the number of items actually deleted, that may be different from the number of IDs passed in case certain IDs do not exist.

redisCommands.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of elements being returned. If N is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with COUNT), you can consider it O(1).
redisCommands.name: XRANGE
redisCommands.summary: Return a range of elements in a stream, with IDs matching the specified IDs interval

redisCommands.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of elements returned. If N is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with COUNT), you can consider it O(1).
redisCommands.name: XREVRANGE
redisCommands.summary: Return a range of elements in a stream, with IDs matching the specified IDs interval, in reverse order (from greater to smaller IDs) compared to XRANGE

redisCommands.name: XLEN
redisCommands.summary: Return the number of entires in a stream

redisCommands.complexity: For each stream mentioned: O(N) with N being the number of elements being returned, it means that XREAD-ing with a fixed COUNT is O(1). Note that when the BLOCK option is used, XADD will pay O(M) time in order to serve the M clients blocked on the stream getting new data.
redisCommands.name: XREAD
redisCommands.summary: Return never seen elements in multiple streams, with IDs greater than the ones reported by the caller for each stream. Can block.

redisCommands.complexity: O(1) for all the subcommands, with the exception of the DESTROY subcommand which takes an additional O(M) time in order to delete the M entries inside the consumer group pending entries list (PEL).
redisCommands.name: XGROUP
redisCommands.summary: Create, destroy, and manage consumer groups.

redisCommands.complexity: For each stream mentioned: O(M) with M being the number of elements returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with COUNT), you can consider it O(1). On the other side when XREADGROUP blocks, XADD will pay the O(N) time in order to serve the N clients blocked on the stream getting new data.
redisCommands.name: XREADGROUP
redisCommands.summary: Return new entries from a stream using a consumer group, or access the history of the pending entries for a given consumer. Can block.

redisCommands.complexity: O(1) for each message ID processed.
redisCommands.name: XACK
redisCommands.summary: Marks a pending message as correctly processed, effectively removing it from the pending entries list of the consumer group. Return value of the command is the number of messages successfully acknowledged, that is, the IDs we were actually able to resolve in the PEL.

redisCommands.complexity: O(log N) with N being the number of messages in the PEL of the consumer group.
redisCommands.name: XCLAIM
redisCommands.summary: Changes (or acquires) ownership of a message in a consumer group, as if the message was delivered to the specified consumer.

redisCommands.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of elements returned, so asking for a small fixed number of entries per call is O(1). When the command returns just the summary it runs in O(1) time assuming the list of consumers is small, otherwise there is additional O(N) time needed to iterate every consumer.
redisCommands.name: XPENDING
redisCommands.summary: Return information and entries from a stream consumer group pending entries list, that are messages fetched but never acknowledged.

redisCommands.name: LATENCY DOCTOR
redisCommands.summary: Return a human readable latency analysis report.

redisCommands.name: LATENCY GRAPH
redisCommands.summary: Return a latency graph for the event.

redisCommands.name: LATENCY HISTORY
redisCommands.summary: Return timestamp-latency samples for the event.

redisCommands.name: LATENCY LATEST
redisCommands.summary: Return the latest latency samples for all events.

redisCommands.name: LATENCY RESET
redisCommands.summary: Reset latency data for one or more events.

redisCommands.name: LATENCY HELP
redisCommands.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands.
